00:09:11,083 --> 00:09:40,855
and when you taste a bit of cheese you presume well this is how the cheese really tastes completely independent of my tongue's ability to taste this is how the cheese tastes and that fallacy really came up with our you know scientific revolution and of course it brought about huge science and technological advantage but it's left us in a bit of a delusion in the sense that

72
00:09:41,289 --> 00:10:09,070
we have this idea that the world and consciousness are two different things that's where the delusion lies so the world as we know it, the world as we experience it can only be experienced by us it can't be experienced by anybody else and that's the world we are actually living in so just a simple for instance of this room so it's not as though

73
00:10:10,264 --> 00:10:38,820
Buddhism would deny the existence of this room if we all left and disappeared it would still be here in some way but our experience of the room as we come in is individual to us so for some it might be a very pleasant room for others I remember when I was at the Vihara once and somebody came to see me who was a very strong Christian and when he walked when I took him into the shrine room you definitely get the feeling that he was walking into the devil's den and there was this sort of

74
00:10:39,322 --> 00:10:42,506
shock, horror, and there's a moment there of resistance.

75
00:10:43,849 --> 00:10:44,470
But he did give in.

76
00:10:46,451 --> 00:10:50,577
So people have different ideas of how a room feels.

77
00:10:50,597 --> 00:10:54,282
They have a different experience of a feeling of a room.

78
00:10:54,383 --> 00:10:56,465
When you walk in, what did you see?

79
00:10:56,725 --> 00:10:58,788
See, some people are very perceptive immediately.

80
00:10:58,807 --> 00:11:01,292
They see the pictures, they see that, but other people don't.

81
00:11:01,312 --> 00:11:04,796
They walk in the room and they walk out, they can't tell you what the hell was in it.

82
00:11:04,816 --> 00:11:05,517
But they've been there.

83
00:11:06,796 --> 00:11:08,519
I can't tell you what the wallpaper was or anything.

84
00:11:08,558 --> 00:11:09,880
It's just the way they are.

85
00:11:09,900 --> 00:11:13,225
They're not particularly interested, we could say.

86
00:11:15,729 --> 00:11:26,024
So even though there are, I think, 11 of us in this room, there isn't a single room in terms of our personal experience, our personal experience of this room.

87
00:11:26,083 --> 00:11:31,351
In other words, as the room exists for us, as the room exists for us,

88
00:11:39,971 --> 00:11:49,945
So if we take that proposition, if we realize that the world I'm living in is actually being manufactured by me, dependent on, of course, the stimuli coming in.

