380
00:45:49,896 --> 00:46:00,208
Now, on the positive side, that's all this negative stuff, on the positive side, remember that that whole process is developing very positive attitudes in us.

381
00:46:00,230 --> 00:46:04,474
It's developing that sense of discriminative inquiry.

382
00:46:04,494 --> 00:46:06,617
It's developing patience and forbearance.

383
00:46:07,117 --> 00:46:11,943
And also, remember, you can flavor your looking with kindness.

384
00:46:12,684 --> 00:46:16,289
So you're looking kindly upon yourself, kindly upon these things.

385
00:46:18,351 --> 00:46:19,632
Now, when it comes to

386
00:46:19,882 --> 00:46:49,333
sorry and the other thing he's developing is this equanimity this complete openness to the way things actually are to see and understand the way things actually are that's the Buddhist phrase it's translated literally to see and understand the way things come to be because the Buddhist question remember is never why we're suffering but how he's not interested in metaphysics he's interested in this process of how we create suffering and in seeing it

387
00:46:49,972 --> 00:46:54,597
He's presuming that we'll see how to end it.

388
00:46:55,079 --> 00:46:56,641
So that's what the vipassana is about.

389
00:46:56,701 --> 00:47:02,648
The vipassana is about seeing this process, to see it as impermanent, to see it as not me, not mine.

390
00:47:03,670 --> 00:47:12,942
But when you then come out of your meditation, you see, there has to be a translation of that understanding into an attitude.

391
00:47:14,182 --> 00:47:15,405
And that's where the metta comes in.

392
00:47:16,010 --> 00:47:39,000
So whereas intellectually or understandingly we might begin to experience or understand this idea of interconnectedness, it remains very dry unless it's turned into an attitude of love, of a quality of love, whether it's sympathetic joy or compassion or any other quality that you can think of which you would put under that large umbrella of good relations.

393
00:47:41,403 --> 00:47:43,266
And that's what the practice of metta does, right?

394
00:47:43,820 --> 00:47:52,568
Now, in some traditions, and you have to agree, it's not absolutely necessary because the wisdom would translate naturally into an attitude.

395
00:47:53,130 --> 00:47:57,054
But it does, I think, help to make that little effort to develop goodwill.

396
00:47:58,615 --> 00:48:06,023
And then that's why every morning there's that point where I remind people to make an act of will for the day.

397
00:48:07,224 --> 00:48:08,927
What is your resolution for the day?

398
00:48:09,447 --> 00:48:11,028
It doesn't matter whether you keep it or not.

399
00:48:11,469 --> 00:48:13,472
What matters is

400
00:48:13,655 --> 00:48:19,280
that you keep, as the Buddha says, inclining to Nibbāna, just leaning in the right way.

401
00:48:19,440 --> 00:48:22,603
So if you lean far enough, you tend to take a step.

402
00:48:23,244 --> 00:48:32,092
So these little resolutions in the morning, which every time you lose it during the day, you reinforce it, they have this effect of making you do it.

403
00:48:32,853 --> 00:48:41,282
There's a rather nice passage in Joseph Goldstein's work, which he wrote about his experience right at the beginning, about the experience of insight.

404
00:48:41,936 --> 00:48:49,347
And if I remember rightly, he would get up very early in the morning to do this meditation and fall asleep.

405
00:48:50,427 --> 00:48:56,016
But he didn't say, oh well, I'm just too tired, it's obviously not working for me, I'll just sleep a bit more.

406
00:48:56,295 --> 00:48:58,518
No, he just kept getting up and going to sleep.

407
00:48:59,079 --> 00:49:03,786
And then one morning, I think two or three months on, he got up and he didn't.

408
00:49:03,806 --> 00:49:05,007
And that's it, that's how it works.

409
00:49:05,579 --> 00:49:10,405
You keep empowering your good intention and you keep tripping over and forth.

410
00:49:10,425 --> 00:49:13,269
You pick yourself up, you dust yourself off, you start all over again.

411
00:49:13,530 --> 00:49:15,992
And then one day, you're doing it.

412
00:49:16,313 --> 00:49:19,577
And it always begins, remember, in the mind, with intention.

413
00:49:20,380 --> 00:49:27,730
So these little resolutions at the end of a sitting, it can be specific to something you're going to have to meet during the day.

414
00:49:28,110 --> 00:49:28,871
It can be general.

415
00:49:29,512 --> 00:49:33,398
And it can be either a negative one, that you're not going to go down that road.

416
00:49:33,958 --> 00:49:35,079
I would always suggest that one.

417
00:49:35,329 --> 00:49:38,554
And a positive one, that this is the path you're going to take.

418
00:49:39,596 --> 00:49:39,856
You see?

419
00:49:40,277 --> 00:49:46,344
And every time you know you've slipped, you reinforce your commitment to those resolutions.

420
00:49:46,364 --> 00:49:49,568
And this immediately begins to have an effect on the way we speak.

421
00:49:49,588 --> 00:49:49,929
You see?

422
00:49:49,969 --> 00:49:50,851
That's right speech.

423
00:49:51,572 --> 00:49:55,016
And then it affects how we just generally behave, right action.

424
00:49:55,938 --> 00:49:58,581
Which is always on an ethical basis.

425
00:49:58,621 --> 00:50:03,547
Because remember, the self, the self is always...

426
00:50:03,882 --> 00:50:25,840
self-endearing it's self-protective it begins you see not from the point of view of evil but from the point of view of delusion and so it feels better if it's bigger and it considers bigger being richer and more powerful and and all that sort of stuff so the more you have in the bank the more happy you feel you might not i mean it's like um

427
00:50:26,106 --> 00:50:27,349
Spike Milligan said, wasn't he?

428
00:50:27,369 --> 00:50:30,612
He said, they say money doesn't make you happy, but I would just like to have a go.

429
00:50:30,632 --> 00:50:36,661
I just want a chance to prove it.

430
00:50:37,641 --> 00:50:47,034
So the self is always trying to substantiate its existence to make itself feel safe.

431
00:50:47,775 --> 00:50:52,521
Remember, that's the fundamental fear of the self, that it is not safe.

432
00:50:53,101 --> 00:50:56,045
That's why it can't handle sickness over age and death.

433
00:50:56,380 --> 00:50:58,081
it doesn't make itself feel safe.

434
00:50:58,702 --> 00:51:07,295
So everything you could say on a positive level when we're working from this particular delusion is just to make ourselves feel safer.

435
00:51:07,996 --> 00:51:11,059
The fact that it's at the expense of everybody else in the world is irrelevant.

436
00:51:13,402 --> 00:51:15,065
What is relevant is that I feel safer.

437
00:51:16,708 --> 00:51:24,057
And so all action in terms of this process of liberation is always around some sort of ethical basis.

438
00:51:25,371 --> 00:51:27,355
And then there's right livelihood.

439
00:51:27,996 --> 00:51:35,186
Now, it's very interesting that the Buddha should put that there, because logically speaking, I suppose you didn't need it, it's included in right action, but he does.

440
00:51:36,086 --> 00:51:55,293
And there's your livelihood, if you think about what the virtues, the traits of your personality, which your actual employment is developing.

441
00:51:56,083 --> 00:52:04,295
So whatever we do for the better part of our lives, those eight or so hours a day, they're having an effect on us.

442
00:52:05,637 --> 00:52:11,166
So somehow we have to make sure that whatever we're doing is done with right attitude.

443
00:52:12,128 --> 00:52:17,797
So if you're doing a brilliant job, begrudgingly, what's the point in terms of this process of liberation?

444
00:52:18,797 --> 00:52:24,706
If you're doing what seemingly might be to other people a menial job or something,

445
00:52:24,956 --> 00:52:52,398
not an important job it is important to that person if they make the decision that this is what I'm going to develop in this work I mean the kernel experience in my life was when I was a kid and I went to work I got this holiday job in this factory making cakes

446
00:52:53,188 --> 00:52:56,512
And it was one of these old belts that came around, these cakes.

447
00:52:57,413 --> 00:53:00,096
And all the women were standing there.

448
00:53:00,175 --> 00:53:03,259
And they put me on the end of the line of these women.

449
00:53:04,039 --> 00:53:06,061
And for them, it was utterly automatic.

450
00:53:06,262 --> 00:53:09,806
My job was to put the cherry on top of this thing as it passed by, you see.

451
00:53:10,465 --> 00:53:13,650
And of course, for them, they were yapping and talking, having a whale of a time.

452
00:53:13,670 --> 00:53:15,490
And they were just doing all this stuff just like that.

453
00:53:15,510 --> 00:53:17,934
You see, when it comes to me, I'm starting to put this damn cherry on.

454
00:53:18,333 --> 00:53:19,195
Every so often, I'd miss.

455
00:53:19,275 --> 00:53:20,275
And the machine had to stop.

456
00:53:20,295 --> 00:53:21,998
And the foreman would be shouting at me.

457
00:53:22,400 --> 00:53:24,922
They were all very kind looking at this boy, you know.

458
00:53:24,943 --> 00:53:25,824
Oh, leave him alone.

459
00:53:28,346 --> 00:53:39,237
And of course, I remember thinking to myself, what a dreadful, what an awful job these poor women have got to come in and do this all day, you know, for eight hours making these cupcakes.

460
00:53:39,257 --> 00:53:47,045
Looking back now, of course, from the point of view of the meditation, what an amazing opportunity to develop concentration.

461
00:53:48,626 --> 00:53:51,309
Moment to moment, concentration on that cake.

462
00:53:51,661 --> 00:53:54,465
As it passes by, cherry spot on in the middle.

463
00:53:54,965 --> 00:53:55,547
Never missing.

464
00:53:56,547 --> 00:53:57,128
Eight hours.

465
00:53:57,489 --> 00:53:59,893
God, I'd have come out enlightened, I'm sure.

466
00:54:00,494 --> 00:54:03,478
I'd have completely liberated from all cakes anyway.

467
00:54:06,442 --> 00:54:08,724
So it doesn't matter what you do, you see, eventually.

468
00:54:08,744 --> 00:54:09,786
It doesn't matter what you do.

469
00:54:09,806 --> 00:54:10,347
It depends.

470
00:54:10,407 --> 00:54:18,059
I mean, apart from the obvious unethical things that we can do, it's the attitude which you're doing.

471
00:54:18,860 --> 00:54:21,043
It's your resolution as to what

472
00:54:21,411 --> 00:54:45,579
your work is that develops in you and to do it for that reason and for doing it when we do something for virtue it automatically benefits the other you don't have to worry about whether it's benefiting the other or not they might not receive it so well but the point is it is to their benefit

473
00:54:58,856 --> 00:55:07,668
And that's how the rest of the path right speech, right action, right livelihood begins to recoil back into the mind.

474
00:55:08,387 --> 00:55:28,172
So where we started in the sitting posture getting that vantage point allowing negative states to arise and burn away beginning to develop that wisdom about who we are, what we are as it moves into daily life it actually is developing these mental states

475
00:55:28,539 --> 00:55:56,016
so that our inner life becomes more and more joyful more and more more and more peaceful that's the theory I can only hope my words have been of some assistance may you by your deep and profound commitment to the practice

476
00:55:57,768 --> 00:56:08,148
move towards your liberation sooner rather than later

